With the schema exactly as written, a true natural root does not exist.
Because parent_page_id is:
* NOT NULL
* a foreign key to another Place.place_page_id
every Place must already point to some other Place.
So if we accept the schema as “right”, then the root has to be a special convention-based root, not a normal null-parent root.
What the root should be
The cleanest choice is a self-parent root place:
* place_page_id = X
* parent_page_id = X
That row is the root of the tree.
Then your hierarchy becomes:
* Australia with parent_page_id = its own id
* Victoria parent = Australia
* Melbourne parent = Victoria
* University of Melbourne parent = Melbourne
* ERC Building parent = University of Melbourne
* Ground Floor Cafe parent = ERC Building
That does not create an infinite loop in application logic if you define:
* root means parent_page_id == place_page_id
Then traversal stops there.
What it should look like
A root place is just a normal Place row backed by a Page, but semantically it is a container, not a real venue.
Example root:
* Page.name = "Australia"
* Place.place_page_id = 1
* Place.parent_page_id = 1
* Place.name = "Australia"
Or you can have multiple seeded roots:
* Australia
* New Zealand
* Global
But each root should still self-parent.
How your code should treat it
When walking up the hierarchy:
while (!current.getPlacePageId().equals(current.getParentPageId())) {
    current = placeRepository.findById(current.getParentPageId()).orElseThrow();
}
So there is no infinite recursion, because the stop condition is:
* place.id == place.parentPlaceId
What I would recommend conceptually
Use a seeded geographic/container hierarchy:
* country root self-parented
* then state
* then city/suburb
* then institution/campus
* then building
* then room/shop/cafe
For your posting feature, new user-created places should usually not become roots. They should attach under an existing container place.
So the answer is: with this schema, the root should be a special seeded self-parenting place, usually something broad like a country, city, or campus.

so how does this schema, this hierarchy make sense? what kind of the feature this db structure want to achieve? How to design the front-end to fit into this db design



Yes, it does make sense as a place graph for social features, but it makes sense only if you read it as a product model, not just as isolated tables.
What This Schema Is Trying To Model
The schema is separating four different ideas:
* Location (line 893) = a physical point/address
* Place (line 424) = a social/business/entity place people can interact with
* Locale (line 919) = “this place exists at this location”, with optional directions
* Place_Tag (line 806) = a post/user being associated with a place
So conceptually:
* Location is map data
* Place is product/social data
* Locale joins them
* Place_Tag uses them inside posts
That is actually a fairly rich idea. It supports things like:
* local business pages
* campus/building/room hierarchies
* event venues
* “I’m here now” check-ins
* “Alice was at ERC Cafe” tagging
* reuse of the same place across many posts/events/users
Why The Hierarchy Exists
The self-reference in Place.parent_page_id -> Place.place_page_id is trying to express containment:
* Australia
* Victoria
* Melbourne
* University of Melbourne
* ERC Building
* Ground Floor Cafe
That lets the product answer questions like:
* show posts from this building
* show posts from this campus including child places
* create a sub-place inside an existing place
* browse places by area/container
So the intended feature is not “every place is equal”. It is “places live inside larger places”.
What Feature Set This DB Seems To Want
This design looks like it wants a Facebook-style mix of:
* pages for venues/businesses
* check-ins and tagged places on posts
* event locations
* hierarchical browsing by area or venue
* multi-level place containers like campus > building > room/shop
Post.place in KooweV1_0_9.sql (line 275) suggests a post has one main attached place.
Place_Tag suggests extra semantics such as:
* tagging other users at that place
* keeping a structured “user was at place in this post” record
* maybe future check-in history
Event.location in KooweV1_0_9.sql (line 233) suggests events use raw locations more directly, while posts use places.
So the schema is basically saying:
* events happen at a Location
* posts are attached to a Place
* a Place can itself be tied to one or more Locations through Locale
Does It Have Weaknesses?
Yes. The idea is reasonable, but the implementation is stricter than ideal because parent_page_id is mandatory. That means the frontend cannot let users create totally free-floating places. It must always place them inside an existing container.
So the frontend should not expose that awkwardness directly.
How To Design The Frontend To Fit This DB
The frontend should present one simple concept to the user: “Add where you are”. Internally, you map that to the schema.
For post creation, I would design this flow:
1. User clicks Add location
2. Show a place picker with:
    * search existing places
    * nearby places from map/GPS
    * recent places
    * create new place
3. If they choose an existing place:
    * send placeId
    * backend stores post.place = placeId
4. If they create a new place:
    * frontend asks for:
        * place name
        * current coordinates/address
        * containing place
    * backend creates:
        * Location
        * Place
        * Locale
    * then stores post.place = newPlaceId
To fit this schema well, the frontend should make the containing place explicit or implicit:
* explicit version:
    * “This place is inside: [University of Melbourne]”
* implicit version:
    * choose from breadcrumbs like Melbourne > University of Melbourne > ERC Building
Best Frontend Pattern
Hide roots and schema complexity. Show users:
* Where are you?
* Choose a place
* Can’t find it? Create it
When creating a place, show:
* Place name
* Address / current map pin
* Inside
    * suburb
    * campus
    * building
    * venue
This maps naturally to the hierarchy.
Recommended UX Structure
For posts:
* one main attached place
* optional “tag people here” action
For place creation:
* quick create under an existing parent
* map pin for actual location
* auto-suggest parent from address if possible
For browsing:
* breadcrumb path like Melbourne / University of Melbourne / ERC Building / Cafe
For events:
* use map/address first
* optionally link to a place later if needed
What The User Should Feel
The user should never see:
* Location
* Locale
* Place_Tag
* parent_page_id
They should only see:
* place
* address
* inside/contained in
* tag location
* tag people here
So the schema is aiming for a structured social-location system. The frontend that fits it best is a place picker + place creator + containment breadcrumb UI, not a raw latitude/longitude form.
