I’m checking what Facebook publicly documents about places, Pages, and location-linked posts so I can separate what we can observe from what we have to infer architecturally.

What Facebook Is Probably Doing
I can’t verify Facebook’s internal implementation, but from public behavior plus Facebook’s own help docs, the safest model is:
* Some location links go to a normal Page with managers.
* Some location links go to a system-generated location hub with no ordinary owner.
* The UI shown depends mostly on page type/category/template, not on a fully free-form page builder.
Public clues:
* Facebook says Pages are for “businesses, brands, organisations and public figures,” and that anyone with access can create/manage one: Create a Facebook Page, Pages.
* Facebook says a Page with a business address and map pin can get tagging/check-ins enabled: Add or edit an address for your Facebook Page.
* Facebook says Page categories change what info/features are available: Add basic information to your Page, What features are available based on your Facebook Page's category.
* Facebook also documents that sections can be added/hidden, but some are fixed: Manage tabs and sections on your Facebook Page, Customize a Page.
So the best inference is: Facebook is not letting every location owner arbitrarily design a completely custom app page. It is much more likely using template-based page types with configurable sections.
Who Owns A “Location Home Page”
You should model 3 cases:
1. Claimed place page A restaurant, store, museum, school, or venue has a real Page and real admins. Owner: business/organization managers via your existing Page_Admin (line 783)-style model.
2. Unclaimed place page A random building, cafe, court, hall, or shop can still have a place page even if nobody officially manages it. Owner: initially nobody, or platform-owned. Your platform can still show:
    * name
    * map
    * address
    * photos from posts
    * recent check-ins/posts
    * nearby places Later, allow a “claim this place” workflow.
3. Geographic area page City, suburb, state, country. This is usually not a business-owned page. It’s more like a discovery/aggregation surface. Owner: platform/system, not the government by default. Its content is aggregated:
    * where to go
    * popular places
    * upcoming events
    * photos/posts in that area
    * guides/categories like “Eat”, “Drink”, “Hotels”
That matches your second screenshot much better than a normal business page. It looks like a location discovery page, not just a raw place profile.
So for your app:
* Place pages can be user/business claimed or unclaimed.
* large geo locations should be treated as system pages.
How To Build This In Koowe
When a user clicks the location text on a post, do not think “jump to the raw Location row.” Think “resolve this post’s place/location into a destination page.”
Use a resolver like:
* if post links to a claimed business place: open that place page
* if post links to an unclaimed place: open an auto-generated place profile
* if post links to a geo area like city/country: open a system discovery page
So you need two concepts:
* Canonical location/place entity This is your data object: Place, Location, Locale.
* Display page This is the UI destination.
A clean product mapping is:
* Location = coordinates/address only
* Place = canonical social place node
* Page = rendered destination surface
* PageType = decides layout/template
Then route like: Post -> Place -> PageResolver -> PageType-specific screen
How The Different Page Layouts Should Work
Do not build a fully arbitrary drag-and-drop page builder first.
Use template families:
* geo_area For country/city/suburb pages. Sections:
* hero/banner
* map
* where to go
* popular places
* events
* recent public posts
* local_business For restaurant/store/cafe. Sections:
* cover/profile
* address/map
* hours/contact
* photos
* reviews
* posts
* events/services
* landmark_or_building For campus/building/hall. Sections:
* overview
* map
* child places
* photos
* recent posts
* venue For event-capable places. Sections:
* venue info
* map
* upcoming events
* posts/photos
That is much closer to how Facebook likely works: same core Page system, different category/template-driven composition.
Can The Owner Freely Customize Everything?
Probably not in the Facebook sense.
Based on Facebook’s public docs, owners can customize:
* basic info
* category-specific fields
* profile/cover
* action buttons
* visible sections/tabs
But the platform still controls the page architecture. So for Koowe, I would recommend:
* owners can edit content
* owners can choose from a few templates
* owners can show/hide sections
* owners cannot arbitrarily invent page structure/components everywhere
That keeps the UX consistent and searchable.
Product Rule I’d Use
For Koowe, define ownership like this:
* geo_area page: system-owned
* local_business page: claimable by org/business
* landmark/building page: unclaimed by default, optionally claimable by org
* venue page: claimable
* random place created from user post: unclaimed auto-generated page first
That gives you a practical answer to “who is in charge?” without requiring every place to already have an official owner.
